As Angular applications grow, architecture becomes far more important than syntax. At a small scale, almost any codebase can work. A few components, a couple of services, and everything feels manageable, but once an application grows — more features, more developers, more business requirements — things start to change.
You begin to notice common problems:

• Components become huge

• Services grow uncontrollably

• Logic gets duplicated

• Features become tightly coupled

• Testing becomes painful

• Small changes break unrelated parts of the application
If you’ve worked on large Angular projects, you’ve probably seen at least a few of these. This is exactly where good design principles become essential.
One of the most valuable sets of design principles in software engineering is SOLID.
If you’re preparing for senior Angular interviews, expect SOLID to come up often. But beyond interviews, these principles genuinely help you build better software. First of all, we need to break SOLID down and understand what it means. SOLID stands for:

• S → Single Responsibility Principle

• O → Open/Closed Principle

• L → Liskov Substitution Principle

• I → Interface Segregation Principle

• D → Dependency Inversion Principle
In this article, I want to explain SOLID from an Angular engineer’s perspective — with practical examples and real-world Angular use cases.

1) Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
The Single Responsibility Principle says:
A class should have only one reason to change.
This sounds simple, but it’s one of the most violated principles in frontend applications. Let’s start with a bad example.
class UserService {
getUsers() {}
saveUsersToFile() {}
sendEmail() {}
}At first glance, this may not look terrible, but this class is doing too much. It handles:

• fetching users

• file storage

• email sending
These are completely different responsibilities. Why is this a problem? Because now this class may change for multiple unrelated reasons:

• API changes

• storage implementation changes

• email logic changes
That’s a design smell. A better approach is to separate responsibilities.
class UserService {
getUsers() {}
}class EmailService {
sendEmail() {}
}
class StorageService {
save() {}
}
Now each class has a clear responsibility, and easier to maintain/test.

SRP in Angular
This principle is extremely important in Angular. One of the most common problems in Angular projects is oversized components.
@Component({})
class DashboardComponent {
fetchUsers() {}
validateForm() {}
sendEmail() {}
}As you noticed, this component handles:

• UI rendering

• data fetching

• form validation

• email logic
That is too much responsibility for a component!
Components should focus on presentation, and services should focus on business logic.
That simple mindset improves architecture dramatically. A cleaner design looks like this:

• Component → UI logic

• Services → business logic

• Utility functions → reusable helpers
This separation keeps components lean and focused. Let’s dive into the next principle, which is OCP.

2) Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
The Open/Closed Principle says:
Software entities should be open for extension, but closed for modification.
In simple terms:
You should be able to add new behavior without modifying existing working code.
This becomes very important in enterprise systems. Why? Because modifying stable code introduces risk.

Bad Example
Imagine payment processing.
class PaymentProcessor {
process(type: string) {
if (type === 'paypal') {}
if (type === 'stripe') {}
}
}Looks fine initially, but after a while, the business says Add Apple Pay as well. Now you must modify the existing class.
class PaymentService {
processPayment(method: string) {
if (method === 'paypal') {
console.log('Pay via PayPal');
} else if (method === 'stripe') {
console.log('Pay via Stripe');
} else if (method === 'applepay') {
console.log('Pay via Apple Pay');
}
}
}Every new payment provider requires changing the working code that violates OCP.

Better Design Using Abstraction
Let’s improve the above example. First, let’s define an abstraction.
interface PaymentMethod {
pay(): void;
}Now create implementations.
class PaypalPayment implements PaymentMethod {
pay() {}
}class StripePayment implements PaymentMethod {
pay() {}
}Now we can extend behavior by adding new implementations. There is no need to modify existing logic, and it's much better now.

OCP in Angular with Dependency Injection
Angular’s dependency injection system makes OCP much easier to implement. Let’s use a more realistic example.
Step 1: Define abstraction.
interface PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number): void;
}Step 2: Create implementations.
@Injectable()
class PaypalService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`PayPal payment: ${amount}`);
}
}@Injectable()
class StripeService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`Stripe payment: ${amount}`);
}
}Step 3: Inject dependency.
@Component({})
class CheckoutComponent {
constructor(private paymentProvider: PaymentProvider) {} checkout() {
this.paymentProvider.pay(100);
}
}
Now the component doesn’t care whether payment happens via:

• PayPal

• Stripe

• Apple Pay
It only cares about this:
paymentProvider.pay()That’s exactly what good abstraction looks like.

How Angular DI Helps
Angular decides which implementation to inject.
Example:
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: PaypalService }
]Let’s suppose the business says Use Stripe instead. You only need to change the provider configuration.
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: StripeService }
]The component stays unchanged. That’s OCP in practice.

Add New Feature (Apple Pay)
Need Apple Pay? Just add a new implementation.
@Injectable()
class ApplePayService implements PaymentProvider {
pay(amount: number) {
console.log(`Apple Pay payment: ${amount}`);
}
}Update provider:
providers: [
{ provide: PaymentProvider, useClass: ApplePayService }
]Done. No component changes required. This is one of Angular’s biggest architectural strengths.

3) Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
The Liskov Substitution Principle says:
Child classes should be replaceable with parent classes without breaking expected behavior.
Classic example:
class Bird {
fly() {}
}class Penguin extends Bird {
fly() {
throw new Error('Cannot fly');
}
}Problem? A penguin is a bird, but it cannot behave as the parent class expects. That violates LSP. This example is famous for a reason. It clearly shows that inheritance is not always the right solution.

LSP in Angular
In Angular, LSP issues usually appear when inheritance is overused. For example:
BaseComponent
BasePageComponent
BaseDashboardComponentThen child components inherit behaviors they don’t actually support, which creates fragile architecture and tight coupling. This is one reason modern Angular architecture often prefers composition over deep inheritance hierarchies.

4) Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
The Interface Segregation Principle says:
Clients should not depend on interfaces they don’t use.
Bad example:
interface Worker {
code(): void;
test(): void;
deploy(): void;
}Problem? Not every worker performs all these tasks. For example:

• Developers may code

• QA engineers may test

• DevOps engineers may deploy
This interface forces unnecessary dependencies, which lead us to bad design.
Better:
interface Developer {
code(): void;
}interface Tester {
test(): void;
}As you noticed, Smaller interfaces are usually better because they are easier to understand and easier to maintain.

ISP in Angular
Interface Segregation becomes very important in Angular applications as projects grow. In theory, everyone agrees that small, focused interfaces are better, but in real projects, I often see Angular codebases full of oversized interfaces. A common example is state management.
interface AppState {
currentUser: User | null;
users: User[];
products: Product[];
cartItems: CartItem[];
selectedProduct: Product | null;
authToken: string | null;
permissions: string[];
orders: Order[];
notifications: Notification[];
}At first, this may seem convenient because everything is in one place, but as the application grows, this becomes painful. Why? Because now unrelated features depend on a giant shared interface.
For example:

• authentication only needs auth-related data

• Product pages only need product state

• The Cart feature only needs cart data
Yet everything depends on the same large structure, which creates unnecessary coupling. A better approach is to split the state by feature.
interface AuthState {
currentUser: User | null;
authToken: string | null;
permissions: string[];
}interface ProductState {
products: Product[];
selectedProduct: Product | null;
}
interface CartState {
cartItems: CartItem[];
}
This design is much cleaner, and its benefits are:

• better separation of concerns

• easier maintenance

• easier scaling

• lower coupling
ISP also applies to services.
Bad example:
interface UserOperations {
getUsers(): void;
createUser(): void;
deleteUser(): void;
exportUsers(): void;
sendEmail(): void;
}Not every consumer needs all these operations. A component that only displays users should not depend on export or email functionality. Smaller contracts usually lead to better architecture. This is one of those principles that becomes more valuable as Angular applications scale

5) Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
This is arguably one of the most important SOLID principles in Angular. In fact, Angular’s entire dependency injection system is heavily built around this idea. The Dependency Inversion Principle says:
High-level modules should not depend on low-level modules. Both should depend on abstractions.
In simpler terms:
Depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations.
This principle helps reduce coupling between different parts of an application. Why does that matter? Tightly coupled systems are difficult to maintain, test, scale, and extend. Let’s look at a simple example.
Bad Example
class UserComponent {
service = new UserService();
}This creates a problem.UserComponent is directly creating its own dependency that means the component is tightly coupled to UserService. Why is that bad? If the implementation changes, the component may need to change too. Angular Improves This with Dependency Injection. This is where Angular shines. Instead of manually creating dependencies, Angular injects them. Example:
constructor(private userService: UserService) {}This is already better.
The component no longer creates the service itself.
Angular handles that responsibility.
This gives us cleaner code, easier testing, and better maintainability, but we can improve even further.
Better with Abstraction
The real power of DIP comes from depending on abstractions instead of concrete implementations. Example:
interface Logger {
log(message: string): void;
}Now our component depends on a contract.
Not a specific implementation.
That’s a major improvement.
Logging Example
Without DI:
class UserComponent {
logger = new ConsoleLogger(); save() {
this.logger.log('saved');
}
}
This works.
But there’s a problem.
What happens if later we want to replace ConsoleLogger with:

• API logger

• file logger

• cloud logger
We must modify the component which violates DIP.
Better Design with DI + Abstraction
First, define abstraction.
interface Logger {
log(message: string): void;
}Now create implementations.
@Injectable()
class ConsoleLogger implements Logger {
log(message: string) {
console.log(message);
}
}@Injectable()
class ApiLogger implements Logger {
log(message: string) {
// send logs to backend
}
}
Now inject dependency.
@Component({})
class UserComponent {
constructor(private logger: Logger) {} save() {
this.logger.log('saved');
}
}
The component no longer cares about implementation details. It only cares that the injected dependency supports:
log()That’s e
